{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"32b072b1-3441-4885-880a-53585d842f95","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues before publishing:\n\n**Functional bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property, so the chosen target framework value will never be substituted into your project files (e.g., `.csproj`). Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or whatever placeholder is in your source) to make it work.\n\n**Missing recommended fields:**\n- **`$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"https://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for editor validation.\n- **`description`** — Important for discoverability on NuGet.org and in `dotnet new list` output.\n- **`defaultName`** — Sets the fallback project name when the user doesn't supply one (e.g., `\"defaultName\": \"MyWebApi1\"`).\n\n**Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all present and correct.\n\nI'd fix the `Framework` symbol and add a `description` at minimum before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"338a3db2-8cba-44ff-af8c-d9a06f685a59","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields per the .NET template engine spec.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The recommended value is `https://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially when you want to group related templates.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Not critical unless there are multiple versions of the template.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, optional.\n   \nThe core fields are in place—identity, name, shortName, author, classifications, tags with language and type, and sourceName for name replacement. However, there's a critical gap: the `description` field is missing, which impacts discoverability in `dotnet new list` and NuGet package listings.\n\nBeyond that, `defaultName` would be helpful though optional, and while `postActions` aren't required, the real functional issue is that the `Framework` symbol lacks a `replaces` property—meaning the framework choice won't actually substitute anything in the template files unless there's conditional logic elsewhere. For NuGet readiness, I'd also want to add the `$schema` reference and ensure that framework selection actually affects the generated output.","outputTokens":785,"requestId":"5008:1031D7:13F2A52:165A2E9:6A06701C"},"id":"b57f15a6-31b9-49cd-bc33-7125dff39595","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:00:29.089Z","parentId":"437f4f4e-56cf-4640-9350-fd78425927ce"}
